  whatItMeans: {
    en: "A month-to-month tenancy is the most flexible kind of rental. There is no fixed end date. The tenancy continues from month to month, automatically renewing each time rent is paid and accepted, until either side ends it with proper notice.\n\nHow a month-to-month tenancy starts. The most common way is by holding over after a written lease ends — when the original lease expires and the tenant stays and pays rent, and the landlord accepts the rent, the tenancy continues on a month-to-month basis. NY Real Property Law § 232-c codifies this. A month-to-month tenancy can also be created from the start by an oral agreement (a 'gentleman's agreement') or by a brief written agreement that says rent is paid monthly with no fixed term.\n\nRent payment and rent increases. The rent stays the same as the prior arrangement unless the landlord properly notices a rent change. To increase rent, the landlord must give the same advance notice as for termination — 30, 60, or 90 days depending on the length of the tenancy. NY RPL § 226-c controls. The notice must be in writing and clearly state the new rent and the effective date. A landlord cannot retroactively increase rent or make the increase effective without proper notice. The 2019 HSTPA introduced the long notice periods to give tenants time to negotiate, plan, or move.\n\nTermination notice — the 30, 60, 90 rule. NY RPL § 232-b (outside NYC) and § 232-a (inside NYC) require written notice of termination. The notice period depends on how long the tenant has lived in the unit. Less than 1 year: 30 days notice. 1 to 2 years: 60 days notice. 2 years or more: 90 days notice. The notice period is the same for the landlord ending the tenancy and for the tenant ending the tenancy. The notice must be in writing, must state the termination date (which must be the end of a rental period), and must be properly served — by personal delivery, by leaving with a person of suitable age at the unit and mailing a copy, or by certified mail with proof of receipt.\n\nWhat counts as the 'length of tenancy.' The length of tenancy includes the original lease period if the tenant rolled into month-to-month at the end of a written lease. A tenant who signed a 1-year lease in 2024 and then rolled into month-to-month for 2025 and 2026 is at the 90-day notice tier (2+ years total occupancy). The clock does not reset when the lease ends.\n\nNo lease, but rent has been paid. A tenant without a written lease who has been paying rent monthly is on a month-to-month tenancy by operation of law. The same NY RPL § 232-b notice rules apply. A landlord cannot kick the tenant out at will — the proper notice must be served and a holdover proceeding filed if the tenant does not leave.\n\nLandlord cannot self-help. NY law absolutely prohibits self-help eviction even on a month-to-month tenancy. NY RPAPL § 768 and NY RPL § 235 make lockouts, utility shutoffs, lock changes, and removal of belongings illegal. The landlord's only legal path is the notice followed by a holdover proceeding if the tenant does not leave. See related entry on holdover tenants.\n\nTenant's rights remain the full rights of a tenant. A month-to-month tenant has the warranty of habitability under NY RPL § 235-b — the unit must be fit for human habitation with working heat, hot water, plumbing, and free of vermin and major defects. The tenant has the right to security deposit return under NY General Obligations Law § 7-103 and § 7-108 (with itemized deduction within 14 days). The tenant has the right to be free from retaliatory termination under NY RPL § 223-b. The tenant has the right to be free from discrimination under NY HRL § 296.\n\nFor tenants planning to move. A tenant ending a month-to-month tenancy gives the landlord the same 30, 60, or 90 days notice that the landlord would owe. The notice should be in writing, identify the unit, state the termination date (the end of a rental period), and be delivered by hand or certified mail with proof. After the notice expires, the tenant moves out and returns keys. The security deposit must be returned within 14 days under HSTPA, with any deductions itemized in writing. The landlord cannot keep the deposit for normal wear and tear.\n\nIf the landlord refuses to accept the notice. Some landlords claim the notice is defective and continue to demand rent past the termination date. The tenant should keep a copy of the notice, proof of service (certified mail receipt), and pay any rent owed up to the termination date. After the termination date, the tenant is no longer obligated to pay rent. If the landlord pursues a small claims action for unpaid rent past the termination date, the proper notice is a complete defense.\n\nFor landlords. A landlord ending a month-to-month tenancy must follow the same 30, 60, or 90 days notice rule. A short notice (e.g., 'leave by next week') is legally ineffective and any holdover proceeding will be dismissed for improper notice. The landlord cannot terminate based on race, color, national origin, religion, sex, disability, familial status, source of income, or other protected characteristic — that is fair housing discrimination. The landlord cannot terminate within 1 year of the tenant's protected activity (code complaint, joining a tenant association) — that is retaliation under NY RPL § 223-b.\n\nFor families and at-risk tenants. The HSTPA notice periods are particularly important for low-income tenants who need 60 to 90 days to find replacement housing in a tight rental market. Tenant Defenders programs and Right to Counsel funding through Legal Aid and JustCause have expanded coverage for month-to-month tenants facing termination."
  },

